### Threads in Rust

Rust uses 1:1 threading where each Rust thread corresponds to one OS thread. The `std::thread` module provides thread creation and management.

---

### Thread Operations

| Function/Method | Description |
|-----------------|-------------|
| `thread::spawn(closure)` | Spawn a new thread |
| `handle.join()` | Wait for thread to finish |
| `thread::sleep(duration)` | Sleep current thread |
| `thread::current()` | Get current thread handle |
| `park()` / `unpark()` | Block/unblock a thread |
| `thread::yield_now()` | Yield to scheduler |

---

### Examples

```rust
use std::thread;
use std::time::Duration;

// Spawning
let handle = thread::spawn(|| {
    for i in 1..10 {
        println!("Thread: {}", i);
        thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(1));
    }
});

for i in 1..5 {
    println!("Main: {}", i);
    thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(1));
}

handle.join().unwrap();  // wait for spawned thread

// Spawning with move closure
let v = vec![1, 2, 3];
let handle = thread::spawn(move || {
    println!("Vector: {:?}", v);  // v is moved into thread
});
handle.join().unwrap();
// println!("{:?}", v);  // ERROR: v was moved
```

> **Key Point:** Use `move` closures with `thread::spawn` to transfer ownership of captured variables. Always join spawned threads to ensure they complete. Threads are OS-level, so creating many threads can be expensive.

codeExample:
use std::thread;
use std::time::Duration;

fn main() {
    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {
        for i in 1..=5 {
            println!("Spawned thread: count {}", i);
            thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(10));
        }
    });

    for i in 1..=3 {
        println!("Main thread: count {}", i);
        thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(10));
    }

    handle.join().expect("Thread panicked");
    println!("All done");
}
